Just try to be aware of anything you can say that can come across that way to anyone.

snippet.textDisplay: When you hear black people say they cannot be racist they are most likely saying it from the sociological perspective. When racism is defined that way it means that it systemically upholds a race superior and gives them advantage over another other politically, socially, and economically. It institutionally oppresses people and upholds certain beliefs. Black people do not have institutional power so their biases cannot be upheld institutionally therefore they cannot oppress a group in that way. That's why people say black people can't be racist. Obviously, when talking about being racist simply in terms of being prejudiced or discriminating against a group based on their race I'm sure everyone knows black people can be "racist." The reality is though that racism is not as simple as being prejudiced or discriminatory. It also implies power and it is systemic. It's individual as well as institutional. Some people benefit from those systems and some are oppressed by them.
